			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/mergers-acquisitions/">Mergers &amp; Acquisitions</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/other-topics/news-analysis/">News Analysis</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">In G.E.&#8217;s Deal for Alstom, French Interventionism Wins Out</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By David Jolly			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-06-23T19:47:29+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">June 23, 2014 3:47 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">June 23, 2014 3:47 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/23/in-g-e-s-deal-for-alstom-french-interventionism-wins-out/" data-title="In G.E.&#8217;s Deal for Alstom, French Interventionism Wins Out" data-description="After much posturing, the French government and G.E. are both declaring victory.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/24/business/dbpix-alstom2/dbpix-alstom2-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/24/business/dbpix-alstom2/dbpix-alstom2-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/24/business/dbpix-alstom2/dbpix-alstom2-blog480.jpg" id="100000002958425" width="480" height="319" alt="An Alstom steam turbine in Belfort, France."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="319"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">An Alstom steam turbine in Belfort, France.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Sebastien Bozon/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">PARIS &#8212; After nearly two months of battle, both  the French government and General Electric can finally declare victory.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And this being France, where argument is considered its own art form, Jeffrey R. Immelt, the G.E. chief, said he  found nothing extraordinary in protracted negotiations with the government  for the right to buy the energy business  of Alstom, one of the countryâs industrial  champions. The final pieces of that <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/22/last-barrier-to-g-e-s-purchase-of-alstom-is-cleared/" title="Last Barrier Is Cleared in G.E.âs Deal With Alstom (June 22, 2014)">$13.5  billion deal fell into place on Sunday</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ââWeâve had a long experience in  France,ââ Mr. Immelt said in a phone interview over the weekend. ââI think we had a  pretty good sense of the context. Itâs  very public and very interesting.ââ</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/24/business/dbpix-alstom/dbpix-alstom-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/24/business/dbpix-alstom/dbpix-alstom-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/24/business/dbpix-alstom/dbpix-alstom-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002958231" width="190" height="127" alt="France&#039;s economy minister, Arnaud Montebourg, said he intervened in G.E.&#039;s bid to protect French interests."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="127"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">France's economy minister, Arnaud Montebourg, said he intervened in G.E.'s bid to protect French interests.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Benoit Tessier/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">French officials, more than in most  other countries, are accustomed to intervening in corporate matters. So  when Bloomberg News broke the news on April 28  that G.E. and Alstom  were already in advanced talks, the  economy minister, Arnaud Montebourg, reacted to it as if to a personal insult. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Although the government had no ownership stake in Alstom until now, Mr. Montebourg saw a symbol of French prowess  being threatened by a foreign takeover.  He accused Alstom of being unpatriotic by negotiating behind his back.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then he helped push through a decree, giving President FranÃ§ois Hollandeâs  government the authority to block the  deal on national security grounds. Not  only did Alstomâs energy business represent more than two-thirds of the 20.3  billion euros, or $27.6 billion, of the companyâs sales last year, it was a crucial link  to the countryâs nuclear establishment. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Montebourg even went so far as to encourage a G.E. rival, the German company Siemens, to make a competing  bid. The pressure worked. G.E. eventually revised its offer in ways to suit Mr.  Montebourg, finally getting the blessing  of the government. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">France could use some outside help  energizing its economy â a message  that was reinforced on Monday by a report from Markit Economics, a data  analysis firm, that showed the country  to be a euro zone laggard. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">G.E. will enter into three joint ventures  with Alstom that will carry the Alstom  name. But the main gas-turbine business  will end up as part of General Electric.  The French government planned to buy  20 percent of what remains of the stand-alone portion of Alstom, which will be a  holding company for the train-manufacturing business and the joint ventures. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ââThe Alstom group has been maintained, with less debt, and made  stronger,ââ Mr. Montebourg told BFM  television on Monday. If the state had  not acted, he added, ââwe would have an Alstom rebranded as General Electric  the world over.ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Immelt said he, too, was happy  with the outcome. ââIt was always our  expectation that we wouldnât do a deal  unless it was good for G.E., good for Alstom, and good for the French government,ââ Mr. Immelt said. ââAnd I think  thatâs what weâve ended up with.ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That ending was far from certain in  late April, when the government learned second-hand of G.E.âs intentions. Patrick  Kron, Alstomâs chairman and chief executive, was summoned from the United  States, where he had been in discussions  with Mr. Immelt, to return to Paris and for a reprimand.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The timing was awkward for Mr. Hollande, who had shuffled his government  less than a month earlier after his Socialist Party suffered losses in local elections. He appointed a new, supposedly more business-friendly prime  minister, Manuel Valls. With unemployment high in France, and the economy  barely growing, Mr. Hollandeâs government wanted to send a message that foreign investors were welcome.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Suddenly, a foreign offer for Alstom  put that newly professed openness to  the test. Alstom employs about 18,000  people in France and is a strong symbol  of French technological might. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Critics in France and abroad have  been quick to accuse Mr. Montebourg, an outspoken socialist, of interfering in  matters better decided by the market.  But government officials in Paris contend that any country facing a foreign  takeover of a player in a strategic industry would have demanded a say â  pointing  to the role played  by the interagency Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In recent years that committee has  challenged Shuanghui Internationalâs takeover of Smithfield Foods,  which it cleared, and Huawei Technologiesâ acquisition of 3Leaf Technology,   which it blocked. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the end, Mr. Immelt led  the campaign to reassure Mr. Hollande,  making three trips to the ÃlysÃ©e Palace  to provide reassurance and offer  sweeteners. By the time Siemens, in  league with Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, made its own offer last week, G.E.  was ready to meet all of the French governmentâs top demands. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The deal that Mr. Montebourg <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/france-to-back-g-e-s-bid-for-alstom-assets/">blessed on Friday</a> gives General Electric the essential assets it had been seeking: Alstomâs gas turbine business and its  valuable customer base. But the American conglomerate agreed to create the alliance structure the government had demanded: 50-50 joint ventures with  Alstom in the areas of renewable energy, steam turbines and nuclear energy, with the government having veto  rights on nuclear contracts.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The arrangement gives Alstom the  right to eventually sell its joint venture  stake to G.E. at a fixed price, Mr. Kron  said during a conference call on Monday, though that seems unlikely as long  as the state remains a shareholder.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The American company also promised  to create 1,000 mainly technical jobs in  France in the next three years and it  agreed to pay a penalty of 50,000 euros for each job that it falls short of that quota. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Montebourg trumpeted the job  agreement on Monday, telling BFM  television: ââThis is the first timeââ for  such a clause, and that ââit could be a precedent.ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Alstom that is left after completion  of the deal will be a listed holding company, housing the French half of the joint  ventures, as well as the rail business. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Alstomâs rail business, which manufacturers the high-speed TGV trains in  Europe and is a global leader locomotives and rail cars, will be strengthened  by the addition of G.E.âs rail signaling  business, which provides the software  and systems to control rail traffic, and a  cooperative deal giving Alstom access  to the United States market.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Immelt said that he was satisfied  with the outcome, and that in the area of  nuclear technology, in particular, ââwe  fully expected that the French governmentâs interests had to be respectedââ to  get a deal. G.E. agreed to give a special  state-owned company control over patents related to Alstomâs advanced Arabelle nuclear steam turbines, and ceded  to the government the final decision on  how that technology should be licensed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Immelt said that the alliance  structure was more complex than his  original proposal, but that G.E. had similar arrangements elsewhere in the world. ââI  think weâre confident that we can put up  the right mechanisms and governance  structures to be successful,ââ he said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He expressed confidence that G.E.  would overcome the few remaining  hurdles and formalities with the deal,  which include discussions with Alstomâs  works councils and a regulatory review  by the French and European Union antitrust authorities.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The deal is G.E.âs largest ever, though  it would rank only second if it were not  for European competition regulators. In  2001, an effort by Mr. Immeltâs predecessor, Jack Welch, to acquire Honeywell International for $42 billion was rejected on antitrust grounds. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Immelt played down fears that the  Alstom deal would stall before the European Commission, noting, ââWeâve had  80 approved by Brussels since then.ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As for his talks with Mr. Montebourg,  Mr. Immelt spoke with diplomatic respect: ââI think heâs a good negotiator;  heâs a professional. He has a purpose  and he has constituents, and so do I.  And we both accomplished what matters for our constituencies.ââ</p>
	</div>
